.TH BITROT-MD5 1 "2026" "bitrot-md5" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bitrot-md5 \- detect bit rot using md5sum\-compatible checksum files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bitrot-md5
.RB [ \-m\ \fIduration\fR ]
.RB [ \-p\ [ =N ]]
.RB [ \-R ]
.RB [ \-r
.IR DIR ]
.RB [ \-s ]
.RB [ \-u
.RI [ FILE ]]
.RB [ \-v ]
.RB [ \-h ]
.RI [ CHECKSUM_FILE ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B bitrot-md5
computes the MD5 hash of every regular file in a directory tree and
compares it against a saved checksum file.
When a hash does not match, the tool distinguishes between two causes:
.TP
.I Bit rot
The file content changed but its modification time is older than or
equal to the checksum file timestamp.
This indicates silent corruption.
.TP
.I Modification
The file content changed and its modification time is newer than the
checksum file timestamp.
This indicates an intentional edit.
.PP
The checksum file uses standard
.BR md5sum (1)
format and can be verified manually with
.BR "md5sum \-c" .
By default, if nothing is changed or wrong, nothing is printed and the
program exits with status 0.
When changes are detected but no
.B \-\-update
file is specified, the updated checksums are written to a temporary
file in
.B $TMPDIR
(or
.I /tmp
if unset) and the path is printed, so the user can review and
.BR mv (1)
it into place.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-m " \fIduration\fP, " \-\-max-time " \fIduration\fP"
Set a time budget for verify mode (e.g.
.BR 30m ,
.BR 1h ,
.BR 45s ).
If the budget is exceeded before all files are checked, the run is
reported as partial.
This option applies only to verify mode and is ignored by
.BR \-u / \-\-update .
.TP
.BR \-p " \fR[\fP" =N "\fR]\fP, " \-\-parallel " \fR[\fP" =N "\fR]\fP"
Enable parallel hashing with
.I N
worker goroutines.
An explicit
.I N
must be joined with
.BR = ,
e.g.
.B \-p=4
or
.BR \-\-parallel=4 .
.B \-p4
is not valid flag syntax, and
.B "\-p 4"
(space\-separated) will not set the worker count either.
If
.I N
is omitted entirely, defaults to the number of available CPUs.
Default: sequential (single thread).
Recommended for SSDs, NVMe drives, and network mounts.
Not recommended for spinning disks, where concurrent reads cause seek
thrashing.
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-random\-order
Check files in a randomized order.
When combined with
.BR \-\-max\-time ,
the set of files checked varies between runs, converging toward full
probabilistic coverage over many runs.
When this flag is set, the filesystem is not scanned for new files:
only files present in the current manifest are checked.
A warning is printed to stderr when this flag is active.
.TP
.BR \-r " \fIdir\fP, " \-\-root " \fIdir\fP"
Directory to scan.
Default: current directory, or the parent directory of the checksum
file if one is specified on the command line.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-summary
Show scan preamble (last scan time and entry count) and summary even
when all files are OK.
.TP
.BR \-u " \fR[\fP" file "\fR]\fP, " \-\-update " \fR[\fP" file "\fR]\fP"
Write updated checksums to
.IR file .
If
.I file
is omitted (bare
.B \-u
or
.BR \-\-update ),
defaults to
.RI DIRNAME .md5
where
.I DIRNAME
is the basename of the current working directory.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Show per\-file verification status.
Implies
.BR \-\-summary .
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display usage information and exit.
.SH CHECKSUM_FILE
The positional argument specifies the checksum file to read.
If omitted:
.TP
.B 1.
If
.B \-\-update
is given, the checksum file defaults to
.I /dev/null
(first run).
.TP
.B 2.
Otherwise, the checksum file defaults to
.RI DIRNAME .md5
in the current directory, where
.I DIRNAME
is the basename of the current working directory.
.PP
If the positional argument is a directory rather than a file, the
checksum file is derived as
.RI DIRNAME / DIRNAME .md5
and the directory is used as the scan root.
.SH DEFAULTS
When run with no arguments from
.IR /path/to/mydata/ :
.IP \(bu 2
Scans the current directory.
.IP \(bu 2
Reads
.IR ./mydata.md5 .
.IP \(bu 2
Writes only to a temporary file unless
.B \-\-update
is given.
.IP \(bu 2
Prints nothing if all files are unchanged.
.SH EXAMPLES
First run, indexing all files in the current directory:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5 -u
.fi
.RE
.PP
Check for corruption (silent if all OK):
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Time\-budgeted verify with randomized order:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5 -m 30m -R /data/backup
.fi
.RE
.PP
Check without \-u, review the temp file, then apply:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5
MODIFIED (1):
  ./docs/report.pdf
    saved:  9c3a2b1e...
    actual: 5f8d1c7a...

Checksums saved to /tmp/bitrot-md5-1234567890.md5
  Verify and apply: mv /tmp/bitrot-md5-1234567890.md5 CHECKSUM_FILE
$ cat /tmp/bitrot-md5-1234567890.md5
$ mv /tmp/bitrot-md5-1234567890.md5 /data/backup.md5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Verbose scan:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5 -v
Last scan : 2026-06-25 14:30:00
Entries   : 1024

./photos/img001.jpg: OK
./photos/img002.jpg: BAD
./docs/report.pdf: MOD

BIT ROT DETECTED (1):
  ./photos/img002.jpg
    saved:  a3f2b8c1...
    actual: 7e1d9f44...

Wrote 1024 entries to /data/.bitrot.md5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Scan a specific directory with parallel hashing:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5 -p=4 -u /mnt/backup/backup.md5 /mnt/backup
.fi
.RE
.PP
Check and update in place:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bitrot-md5 -u .bitrot.md5 .bitrot.md5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Verify manually with standard tools:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ cd /mnt/backup && md5sum -c backup.md5
.fi
.RE
.SH VERBOSITY
With
.BR \-v / \-\-verbose ,
each file is printed on its own line with a status tag:
.TP
.B OK
Hash matches the saved value.
.TP
.B BAD
Hash changed, mtime older than checksum file.
Indicates bit rot.
.TP
.B MOD
Hash changed, mtime newer than checksum file.
Indicates intentional modification.
.TP
.B NEW
File not present in the previous checksum file.
.TP
.B DELETED
File was in the previous checksum file but no longer exists.
.TP
.B ERROR
File could not be read.
.SH FILE_FORMAT
Standard
.BR md5sum (1)
output format: each line contains a 32\-character MD5 hex digest,
two spaces, and the relative file path with a
.B ./
prefix.
.SH EXCLUSIONS
.TP
\(bu
Regular files only: symlinks, device files, FIFOs, and sockets are
skipped.
.TP
\(bu
Hidden directories (names starting with
.BR . )
are skipped.
.TP
\(bu
The checksum input and output files themselves are excluded from scanning.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Exit codes are bitwise\-composed from three flags (bit 0: problem
detected, bit 4: partial run, bit 5: random\-order run).
Code 15 is a standalone usage error.
.TP
.B 0
No issues detected.
.TP
.B 1
Bit rot or file access errors detected.
.TP
.B 15
Usage error.
.TP
.B 16
Partial run (
.B \-\-max\-time
exceeded, no bit rot).
.TP
.B 17
Partial run (
.B \-\-max\-time
exceeded, bit rot detected).
.TP
.B 32
Random\-order run (filesystem scan skipped), no problems.
.TP
.B 33
Random\-order run (filesystem scan skipped), problems detected.
.TP
.B 48
Partial and random\-order run, no problems.
.TP
.B 49
Partial and random\-order run, problems detected.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B GOMAXPROCS
Influences the default number of parallel workers when
.B \-\-parallel
is used without an explicit count.
.SH NOTES
MD5 is sufficient for bit rot detection.
A random bit flip has a 2^128 chance of producing the same
digest \(em one undetected error per ~10^38 bits.
The known collision attacks against MD5 require crafted inputs and are
irrelevant for detecting accidental corruption.
.PP
No per\-file timestamps are stored.
The checksum file's modification time serves as the single "last known
good" timestamp.
.PP
For repositories too large to check in a single nightly window,
.B \-\-max\-time
with
.B \-\-random\-order
provides probabilistic coverage over time.
The randomized shuffle ensures different subsets are checked each run,
converging toward full coverage.
Full (unbounded) runs should be performed periodically as a completeness
backstop.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR md5sum (1),
.BR find (1)
